<subSubSection pageId="159" pageNumber="762" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="159.[781,1372,2471,2889]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[781,994,2581,2615]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Dasymys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="159" pageNumber="762" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="medius">Dasymys medius</taxonomicName>
, previously considered to be part of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sundevall" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[928,1083,2625,2654]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Dasymys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="159" pageNumber="762" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="incomtus">D. incomtus</taxonomicName>
, was elevated to spe- cies rank on basis of molecular and morphological data, although genetic distances (from cytochrome-b gene sequences) between it and 
<taxonomicName box="[1004,1090,2782,2811]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Dasymys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="159" pageNumber="762" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sua">D. sua</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Verheyen, Hulselmans, Dierckx, Colyn, Leirs &amp; E. Verheyen" authorityYear="2003" box="[1165,1319,2782,2811]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Dasymys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="159" pageNumber="762" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rwandae">D. rwandae</taxonomicName>
are less than 2%. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="159" pageNumber="762" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6887858" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6887858" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6887858/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="159" pageNumber="762" startId="159.[781,954,2855,2889]" targetBox="[167,757,2473,2886]" targetPageId="159">
<paragraph blockId="159.[781,1372,2471,2889]" lastBlockId="159.[165,1371,2904,3479]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[781,957,2855,2889]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762">Distribution.</emphasis>
Mountains of Albertine Rift and East African Rift, at elevations of up to 2600 m.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="159" pageNumber="762" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="159.[165,1371,2904,3479]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[167,420,2943,2968]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 150 mm, tail 134 mm, ear 20 mm, hindfoot 30 mm; weight 107 g. Like all 
<taxonomicName box="[479,589,2974,3008]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Dasymys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="159" pageNumber="762" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Dasymys</taxonomicName>
, the Middle ShaggyRat has fur that is soft, shaggy, and long-haired, and is reddish brown dorsally and dull gray ventrally. Head is broad, with short muzzle, the vibrissae long, and ears rounded and well furred on inside. Tail is ¢.10% shorter than head-body length, heavily scaled, sparsely haired, and darker above than below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[167,656,3175,3204]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="159.[165,1371,2904,3479]" box="[167,656,3175,3204]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[167,278,3175,3204]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762">Habitat.</emphasis>
Swampy areas in wetlands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[167,1153,3210,3244]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="159.[165,1371,2904,3479]" box="[167,1153,3210,3244]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[167,429,3210,3244]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
The Middle Shaggy Rat is presumably herbivorous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[167,540,3254,3283]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762" type="breeding">
